  <div class="col-md-8 mb-4 mb-md-0 d-flex flex-column justify-content-center" style="position: relative; z-index: 1;">
    <div class="case-study-info">
      <h5 class="mb-2">Filter Panel</h5>
      <p>The filter panel was modeled after the market research that was done for the project. Products like Amazon, Walmart, Shopify templates, and other recognition-style software formed the foundation of the standard type of sorting/filtering expected.</p>
      <p>It was important that it didn’t feel too far away from the regular controls used in Workhub for filtering and sorting. Creating wildly non-standard UI was something I was tasked with reducing as much as possible. This solution was a nice compromise between high utility and consistency.</p>
      <p>Key brand features like enumerating how many items were in the catalog at that moment, point range with a new “Quick limit” to that users point total, and tag-based filtering were added to create a truly enjoyable “discovery-style” experience with the aim of helping a user find whatever they’re interesting in in the catalog as quickly as possible.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

